'''"Trapped in the Closet"''', the twelfth episode of the [[List_of_South_Park_episodes#Season_9:_2005|ninth season]] of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[South Park]]'', originally aired on [[November 16]], [[2005]].  The plot of the episode centers on the ''South Park'' character [[Stan Marsh]], as he joins [[Scientology]] in an attempt to find something "fun and free". After the discovery of his surprisingly high "[[thetan]] levels", he is recognized as the reincarnation of the founder of the church, [[L. Ron Hubbard]].

Though the episode was originally scheduled for rebroadcast in March 2006, the episode "[[Chef's Chocolate Salty Balls]]" was shown instead.  Comedy Central representatives stated this change was made as a tribute to Isaac Hayes, however ''South Park'' creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] thought otherwise. Stone and Parker issued a satirical statement saying they were "servants of the dark lord [[Xenu]]". [[Isaac Hayes]], the voice of [[Chef (South Park)|Chef]], quit the show shortly before the start of the tenth season. The reason for his departure, as reported by [[Matt Stone]], was due to his faith in Scientology and this episode, which <U+2014> despite initially supporting the show's satirical take on several talk shows <U+2014> he claimed to feel was very offensive.

"Trapped in the Closet" was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in July 2006, but the ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode "[[The Seemingly Never-Ending Story]]" eventually received the award in the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming less than One Hour)]] category. The episode was featured among [[Comedy Central]]'s list of "10 South Parks That Changed The World", spoofed by [[Conan O'Brien]] in the opening segment of the [[58th Primetime Emmy Awards]], and mentioned in the Scientology critique film, ''[[The Bridge (Scientology film)|The Bridge]]''.

==Plot==
Stan takes a "[[Oxford Capacity Analysis|personality test]]" that is being offered by Scientologists on the street. After answering a long [[questionnaire]], Stan is informed that he is a perfect candidate for Scientology &mdash; they offer to help him out for $240. Back at home, Stan asks his parents for money to help with his depression and his father suggests he use the money he had been saving for a new bike.<ref name="comedycentralsite">{{cite web
  | last = Staff, Comedy Central Web site
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title = Trapped in the Closet, clips, "It's Always Free at First", "Off the Charts", and "Things Scientologists Actually Believe."
  | work = [[South Park]]
  | publisher = [[Comedy Central]]
  | date = Air date: 11/16/2005 
  | url = http://southpark.comedycentral.com/video_by_episode.jhtml?episodeId=103804
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  2007-10-20}}</ref> After he pays, Stan is taken into an [[Auditing (Scientology)|auditing]] room and an attendant reads his "[[thetan]] levels" using an "[[E-meter]]", Michelle is shocked by the high reading, and Stan's results are faxed to the Scientology headquarters in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]]. There, the president of Scientology determines that, because his reading is so high, Stan must be a reincarnation of [[L. Ron Hubbard]], Scientology's founder and [[prophet]].<ref name="comedycentralsite" />

Back in South Park, a large group of Scientologists, including [[John Travolta]], have gathered outside to celebrate Stan's "second coming". The President of Scientology arrives in a helicopter and talks with Stan's parents. Stan's parents oppose his being in the group, but the president informs [[Randy and Sharon Marsh]] that, "We're not asking him to ''join'' us; we're asking him to ''lead'' us." Randy sends his son Stan, confused and exhausted, to his room where he finds Tom Cruise waiting for him. Cruise, thinking Stan is genuinely Hubbard's reincarnation, asks him whether he enjoyed his acting. When Stan tells Cruise that his acting is not as good as others, Tom locks himself in Stan's bedroom closet, believing he is a failure in the eyes of the "prophet". He refuses to come out, despite Randy, [[Nicole Kidman]], John Travolta and [[R. Kelly]]'s attempts to persuade him to come out of the closet, with R. Kelly's repeated narrative similar to his [[Rap opera|hip-hop opera]] piece [[Trapped in the Closet]]. 

Downstairs, the Scientology president tries to convince Stan's parents to let their son join them. They want to reveal the great secret of life behind their church to Stan. Randy asks his son if he would like to know this information and Stan responds with a "sure". The president tells him a condensed version of the story of [[Xenu]], based directly on the actual Scientology [[Operating Thetan|OT]] III document,<ref name="arp" /> and accompanied by an onscreen caption reading, "this is what Scientologists actually believe". After explaining these beliefs, he tells Stan to continue writing where "L. Ron" left off. On the official Comedy Central Web site for the ''South Park'' episode, it is asserted that this section of "Trapped in the Closet" was not exaggerated: "Nothing about what you see here is exaggerated in the slightest. Seriously."<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Staff, Comedy Central Web site
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title = Things Scientologists Actually Believe
  | work = [[South Park]]
  | publisher = [[Comedy Central]]
  | date = Air date: 11/16/2005 
  | url = http://southpark.comedycentral.com/videos.jhtml?videoId=104274&episodeId=103804
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =  2007-10-20}}<br>The head of the Church of Scientology tells Stan the creation myth that Scientologists actually believe. Nothing about what you see here is exaggerated in the slightest. Seriously.</ref>

Stan begins writing and, when Kyle, Cartman, and Kenny come over to invite him to the movie theater, he doesn't have time for them. Kyle is concerned about the cult that Stan has joined, but Stan assures him that Scientology is based on fact. If they can't accept that he has found meaning then they are no longer friends. Stan shows his writings to the Scientology president, who approves of most of his work, but, when Stan says, "to really be a church, [they] can't charge money to help," the president reveals to Stan that the church is a money-making scam.

[[Image:Sp 912.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Stan is presented to the Scientologists]]
Outside the house, the president introduces Stan to his followers, to whom he will read his new [[doctrine]]. However, instead of presenting it to them, Stan reveals that he is actually not the reincarnation of L. Ron Hubbard, and that: "Scientology is just a big fat global scam." His followers grow angry, and threaten to sue him. Tom Cruise leaves Stan's closet and appear, threatening to sue him. Stan dares them to do so, and the episode ends with the credits listing only "John Smith" and "Jane Smith", a reference to Tom Cruise and the Church of Scientology's reputations for litigiousness.<ref name="Hilden">{{cite news|url=http://writ.news.findlaw.com/hilden/20051206.html|title=
Could Tom Cruise Sue "South Park" For Suggesting He is Gay? And Even If He Could, Should He?|accessdate=2006-08-16|last=Hilden|first=Julie|date=[[2005-12-06]]|publisher=[[FindLaw]]}}</ref><ref name="Cruises to the Emmys">{{cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2006/07/06/south-park-cruises-to-the-emmys/|title="South Park" Cruises to the Emmys|accessdate=2006-08-16|author=TMZ Staff|date=[[2006-07-06]] |publisher=TMZ.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Chonin|first=Neva|title=Cruise Control|work=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=2006 Hearst Communications Inc.|date=[[2006-03-26]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/03/26/PKGU9GIP131.DTL|accessdate=2007-10-20}}</ref>

== Production ==
''South Park'' had previously [[parody|parodied]] Scientology in a spoof at the 2000 [[MTV Movie Awards]].<ref name="ortega">{{cite news 
  | last = Ortega
  | first = Tony
  | coauthors =
  | title = Sympathy For The Devil: Tory Bezazian was a veteran Scientologist who loved going after church critics. Until she met the darkest detractor of all. 
  | work = New Times Los Angeles
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = [[September 27]], [[2001]]
