  | date = [[June 8]], [[2000]]
  | url = http://www.xenutv.com/us/mtvawards.htm
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  The MTV short was entitled: "The Gauntlet," and it included "John Travolta and the Church of Scientology" arriving in a spaceship to defeat [[Russell Crowe]] (as a [[Gladiator (film)|Gladiator]]) and attempt to recruit the boys into Scientology. Travolta, along with his fellow Scientologists, was depicted as a Psychlo, as he appeared in the film ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]''.<ref name="mtv" /> They had also made fun of Scientology in an earlier episode, entitled ''[[Super Best Friends]]'', in which [[David Blaine]] formed his own [[cult]], called "Blaintology".<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = de Moraes 
  | first = Lisa
  | coauthors =
  | title = Comedy Central Again Steals 'South Park' Thunder
  | work = [[The Washington Post]]
  | pages = Page C01
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = April 14, 2006
  | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/13/AR2006041302212.html?nav=rss_print/style
  | accessdate =  2007-10-21}}
</ref> Parker and Stone have admitted that this is meant to be a reference to Scientology.<ref>Episode Commentary on ''South Park'': Season 5 DVD boxset.</ref> 

Trey Parker asserts that Isaac Hayes' beliefs had previously kept the show's creators from writing a full-episode which parodies Scientology. However, the decision to ultimately produce a ''South Park'' episode satirizing Scientology was partially inspired by the friendship the show's creators have with [[Penn Jillette]].  Jillette was originally planning to do an episode of ''[[Penn & Teller: Bullshit!|Bullshit!]]'' based on Scientology, but [[Showtime]] prohibited him from doing so to avoid the possibility of legal action from the Church of Scientology.  Trey Parker stated: {{Quotation|"We're going, That's fucked up. And hearing other people say, 'You can't do that,' <U+2014> you can only say 'You can't do that' so many times to Matt and me before we're gonna do it. Finally, we just had to tell Isaac, 'Dude, we totally love working with you, and this is nothing personal, it's just we're South Park, and if we don't do this, we're belittling everything else we've ripped on.'"<ref name="Scientology">{{cite news|url=http://men.style.com/gq/features/full?id=content_4108&pageNum=4|title=They Killed Kenny<U+2026>And Revolutionized Comedy|publisher=men.style.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref>}}

During production on the episode, [[investigative journalism|investigative journalist]] [[Mark Ebner]] served as a consultant to Matt Stone and Trey Parker.<ref name="ebner">{{cite web
   |url        = http://www.hollywoodinterrupted.com/archives/hollywood_interrupted_basks_in_the_glow_of_a_south_park_emmy_nod.phtml
