==Controversy==
===Isaac Hayes' departure===
On [[March 13]], [[2006]], Hayes announced that he was quitting the show because of the series' treatment of religion, though he didn't specifically mention Scientology in his statement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/religion/Story/0,,1731115,00.html|title=Isaac Hayes quits South Park after it satirises Scientology|accessdate=2007-03-06}}</ref> In an interview on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Showbiz Tonight]]'', he added he didn't see the episode itself, but was told about it.<ref>{{cite news|last=Morales|first=Lisa|title=Everyone's in a Stew Over 'South Park' Chef|work=[[The Washington Post]]|pages=The TV Column, p. 2 of 2.|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=[[2006-03-17]]|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/17/AR2006031702158_2.html?nav=hcmodule|accessdate=2007-06-17}}</ref> He reportedly said to Parker and Stone, "Guys, you have it all wrong. We're not like that. I know that's your thing, but get your information correct, because somebody might believe that shit, you know? But I understand what they're doing. I told them to take a couple of Scientology courses, and understand what we do. [Laughs]."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/44132/2|title=Isaac Hayes Interview|publisher=avclub.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref>

Responding to Hayes' departure, Stone stated "This is 100 percent having to do with his faith of Scientology... He has no problem <U+2014> and he's cashed plenty of checks <U+2014> with our show making fun of Christians {{interp|...}} He wants a different standard for religions other than his own, and, to me, that is where intolerance and bigotry begin."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?news=218421&GT1=7703|title=Isaac Hayes Quits 'South Park'|publisher=entertainment.msn.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> However, recent reports say that Hayes was in no condition to stay, because of a stroke he suffered in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,188463,00.html|title=Chef's Quitting Controversy|publisher=foxnews.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> According to a Fox News article, Hayes' agent Christina Kimball, herself a devout Scientologist, was the source of the statements that Hayes quit South Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,188720,00.html|title=Bruce Willis Gets Lucky, But Not With Model|publisher=foxnews.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref>

There were many conflicting stories as to the exact nature of Hayes' departure. Additional reasons given by Hayes ten months after the departure include "They didn't pay me enough," and: "They weren't that nice."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/01242007/gossip/pagesix/isaac_puts_chef_behind_him_pagesix_.htm|title=Isaac puts Chef behind him|publisher=The New York Post|date=2007-1-24|accessdate=2007-01-25}}</ref> In a 2007 interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Stone stated, "There are reports that Isaac had a stroke and Scientology quit the show for him, and I believe it...It was a brutal, up-close, personal thing with Isaac. If you look at the timeline, something doesn't add up."<ref> {{cite news|last=Grigoriadis|first=Vanessa|authorlink=Vanessa Grigoriadis|title=Still Sick, Still Wrong : For ten years, "South Park" has been the crudest, stupidest, most offensive show on television. And the funniest.|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|pages=Cover Story|date=[[2007-03-22]]|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/south_park_still_sick_still_wrong/page/1|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref>

Due to the absence of Hayes, Chef was voiced in "[[The Return of Chef]]" using pre-recorded snippets of dialog culled from previous episodes, and was written out of the series by the episode's ending.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogcritics.org/archives/2006/03/24/010757.php|title=TV Review: South Park "The Return of Adam Livshits"|work=blogcritics.org|first=Al|last=Barger|date=2006-03-24|accessdate=2006-11-28}}</ref>

=== "Closetgate" ===
[[Image:Cmonjews.jpg|right|thumb|"C'mon Jews, show them who ''really'' runs Hollywood" - Comedy Central advertisement, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]],'' [[August 1]], [[2006]]]]
This episode was scheduled to rebroadcast on [[March 15]], [[2006]] on Comedy Central, but the airing was canceled without prior notice, and was replaced with "[[Chef's Chocolate Salty Balls]]". Representatives of Comedy Central insist that the episode was changed as a tribute to Isaac Hayes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-southparkscientologyepisodepulled,0,4332947.story|title=Did 'South Park' Get Cruised?|publisher=zap2it.com|date=2006-03-17|accessdate=2007-06-15}}</ref>  The episode did not broadcast on [[Paramount Comedy 1]] as well, although every other episode of the season has been. Reportedly, the channel directors did not air it to avoid a possible lawsuit against the channel by Cruise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2-2006020708,00.html|title=Cruise axe for South Park|publisher=thesun.co.uk|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref>  

The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' dubbed the controversy surrounding the episode's rebroadcast: "[[List of scandals with "-gate" suffix|Closetgate]]."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Collins
  | first = Scott
  | coauthors =
  | title = CHANNEL ISLAND; Clamor outside `South Park' closet; `Mission: Impossible' studio joins Cruise's camp in denying it strong-armed scrapping of Scientology repeat.
  | work = [[Los Angeles Times]]
  | pages = Calendar Desk; Part E; Pg. 16
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = March 18, 2006
  | url =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  ''[[The Independent]]'' later cited the ''Los Angeles Times'', noting that the controversy generated positive publicity for the show's creators: "For Stone and Parker, Closetgate will be the gift that keeps on giving."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Usborne 
  | first = David 
  | coauthors =
  | title = South Park declares war on Tom Cruise; Cartoon's parody of Scientology is taken off air, prompting accusations of censorship.
  | work = [[The Independent]]
  | pages = NEWS; Pg. 44
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = March 19, 2006
  | url = http://news.independent.co.uk/media/article352197.ece
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref>  "Closetgate" has since been used to refer to the "brouhaha" surrounding Isaac Hayes' departure and rebroadcasts of the episode, by other news sources including the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''.<ref name="emerson">{{cite news 
  | last = Emerson
  | first = Jim
