When asked in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Primetime'' about his involvement with stopping the episode rebroadcast on Comedy Central, Cruise stated "First of all, could you ever imagine sitting down with anyone? I would never sit down with someone and question them on their beliefs. Here's the thing: I'm really not even going to dignify this. I honestly didn't really even know about it. I'm working, making my movie, I've got my family. I'm busy. I don't spend my days going, 'What are people saying about me?'"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Cruise_No_Oprah_Regrets/3491532|title=Cruise: 'No Oprah Regrets'|publisher=hollywood.com|date=2006-04-16|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref> A representative of Cruise had also denied any involvement of Cruise with the issue, specifically responding to allegations of Cruise's reputed corporate power play.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2-2006020708,00.html|title=Cruise axe for South Park|publisher=thesun.co.uk|date=2006-03-17|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref>

In May 2006, "Trapped in the Closet" was shown in [[London, England]], at the National Film Theatre. The free screening was followed by a discussion with Trey Parker and Matt Stone, who said the screening was a "display of free speech."<ref name="ninemsnstaff">{{cite news 
  | last = Staff
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title = Cruise loses 'South Park' battle
  | work = [[National Nine News]]
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = 1997- 2007 ninemsn Pty Ltd
  | date = May 19, 2006
  | url = http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=102210
  | accessdate =  }}</ref> Free copies of the episode were given out to attendees after the screening.<ref name="ninemsnstaff" /> Complaints from Tom Cruise had previously prevented the episode from airing in Britain in January 2006.<ref name="ninemsnstaff" />

On [[July 19]], [[2006]], Comedy Central did air a rebroadcast of the episode at 10:00 [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]]<ref name="timgoodman" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/718/718226p1.html|title=South Park "Trapped in the Closet" Episode to Air Again|publisher=tv.ign.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> and did so again on [[July 23]], [[2006]] at 11:00pm Eastern Time and on [[September 24]] at 10:00 PM Eastern time. Matt Stone stated "If they hadn't put this episode back on the air, we'd have had serious issues, and we wouldn't be doing anything else with them."<ref>{{cite news|last=Staff|coauthors=[[Associated Press]]|title=<U+2018>South Park' Scientology episode set to rerun: Show that pokes fun at Tom Cruise was abruptly pulled back in March|work=[[MSNBC]]|publisher=[[NBC]]|date=[[2006-09-12]]|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/13834457/|accessdate=2007-03-16}}</ref>  After the episode was scheduled to be rebroadcast, Trey Parker and Matt Stone were interviewed on [[CNN]]'s ''[[Showbiz Tonight]]'', where they stated that all of the controversy increased publicity for the episode.<ref name="showbiz06">{{cite news 
  | last = Hammer
  | first = A.J.
  | coauthors = Mary Murphy, TV Guide
  | title = Cruise and South Park; Princess Di Photos; Movie Reviews; Technology Addiction
  | work = [[Showbiz Tonight]]
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = [[CNN]]
  | date = July 14, 2006
  | url = http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0607/14/sbt.01.html
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> Parker was quoted: "But it`s really like a publicist couldn`t have orchestrated this any better for us. You know what I mean? It`s like it`s been phenomenal. Tom Cruise has done more for "South Park" than anyone I think in the world."<ref name="showbiz06" />

The episode was released in several DVDs, including ''South Park the Hits: Volume 1''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/news/display_news.php?month=8&year=2006|title=South Park Studios: News|publisher=southparkstudios.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> and ''South Park: The Complete Ninth Season'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ent/4603365.html|title=Entertainment: More Naughty Fun|publisher=''[[Houston Chronicle]]''|author=Westbrook, Bruce|date=2007-03-06|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> in contradiction with an alleged request by either the Church of Scientology or Cruise to never put the episode on DVD format.<ref name="timgoodman">{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Tim|title=Death March With Cocktails: 'South Park' at 10 trumps Tom Cruise|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=Hearst Communications Inc.|date=[[2006-07-15]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/07/15/DDG6LJU24T1.DTL|accessdate=2007-10-20}}</ref>

===Aftermath===
[[Image:South Park Scientology grafitti.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Matt and Trey depicted spray-painting graffiti on the church's [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]] headquarters sign as a reference to the controversy]]
A few references have been made by the show and Comedy Central to Scientology as an aftermath of the controversy. On [[August 1]], [[2006]], Comedy Central placed an advertisement in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' showing the ''South Park'' stars against a background of [[Celebrity Centre|L. Ron Hubbard's Scientology Celebrity Center]], with the headline, "C'mon Jews, show them who ''really'' runs Hollywood."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Leonard
  | first = Devin
  | coauthors =
  | title = 'South Park' creators haven't lost their edge
  | work = Fortune
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = Time Warner
  | date = October 27 2006
  | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2006/10/30/8391792/?postversion=2006102716 
  | accessdate =  }}<br>"Trapped in the Closet" was nominated for an Emmy in July. The network showed its appreciation by running a full-page ad in Variety with the "South Park" boys saying, "C'mon, Jews! Show them who really runs Hollywood." The episode has been rerun many times since.</ref> Although often misunderstood by the public to parody the [[Mel Gibson DUI incident]], the advertisement actually congratulates ''South Park'' on gaining an Emmy nomination for "Trapped in the Closet" and satirizes the cancellation of the episode's rebroadcast in March.<ref>{{cite news|last=Finn|first=Natalie|title="Passion of the Jew" Part 2? Not Quite|work=[[E! Online]]|publisher=E! Entertainment Television, Inc.|date=[[2006-08-02]]|url=http://www.eonline.com/news//article/index.jsp?uuid=81361eaa-62e9-4557-b025-703abf806f60&entry=index|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Network_Execs_Deny_South_Park_Ad_Targeted_Gibson/3539459|title=Network execs deny South Park ad targeted Gibson|publisher=hollywood.com|date=2006-08-02|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref>

A different reference to Scientology was made accompanying the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' cover article ''Still Sick, Still Wrong'' celebrating the show's anniversary. The reference portrayed a likely altered photo of Matt and Trey spray-painting graffiti on the church's [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]] headquarters sign, which includes "Is dum" and "Hi Tom" messages with a depiction of Cartman's head.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070309/ENTERTAIN/70309020|title=<U+2018>South Park' sticks it to Scientology again|publisher=recordonline.com|first=Robin A.|last=Rothman|coauthors=Tomcho, Sandy|date=2007-03-09|accessdate=2007-03-11}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Reviews===
In a review of ''South Park: The Complete Ninth Season'', [[IGN]] stated that "Perhaps the largest weakness of this season is that the most notorious episodes ''[[Best Friends Forever]]'' and ''Trapped in the Closet'' just don't carry the eye-popping impact that they did when they were ripped from the headlines", giving the DVD a rating of 7.0.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/768/768477p1.html|title=South Park - The Complete Ninth Season|publisher=tv.ign.com|author=Schorn, Peter|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref>  

''[[The Denver Post]]'' stated the jokes about Tom Cruise "work splendidly and reveal their depth on repeated viewings, much like the show in general."<ref>{{cite news|last=Wenzel|first=John|title="South Park" becomes a gem|work=[[Denver Post]]|date=[[2007-03-19]]|url=http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_5475880|accessdate=2007-10-20}}
</ref> ''[[San Francisco Chronicle|The San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote that Matt Stone and Trey Parker "probably hit their zenith when they made fun of Tom Cruise and Scientology".<ref name="timgoodman" />

===Analysis===
An article in the ''Journal of the American Academy of Religion'' referred to the episode as a "scathing cartoon parody" of the Church of Scientology.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Urban|first=Hugh B.|title=Fair Game: Secrecy, Security, and the Church of Scientology in Cold War America|url=http://jaar.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/74/2/356 (abstract)|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Religion|volume=74|issue=2|pages=356<U+2014>389|publisher=[[American Academy of Religion]]|date=[[2006-04-26]]|id={{ISSN|1477-4585}}, {{ISSN|0002-7189}}|accessdate=2007-10-20}}
</ref>

[[University of Delaware]] [[philosophy]] professor [[Richard Hanley]] analyzed the mythology of Scientology as it relates to the episode "Trapped in the Closet," in his 2007 book: ''[[South Park and Philosophy: Bigger, Longer, and More Penetrating]]''.<ref name="hanley">{{cite book|last=Hanley|first=Richard|title=[[South Park and Philosophy: Bigger, Longer, and More Penetrating]]|publisher=Open Court|date=[[2007-03-28]]|pages=23, 24, 32, 41, 246, 247, 262, 283|id=ISBN 0812696131}}</ref><ref name="greto">{{cite news|last=Greto|first=Victor|title=I offend, therefore I am: University of Delaware professor aimed for 'rude and crude ' in his book on 'South Park'|work=The News Journal, Delaware Online|publisher=USA Today, Gannett|date=[[2007-04-02]]|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070402/LIFE/304020301/-1/NEWS01|accessdate=2007-10-20}}</ref> Hanley called the [[Xenu|Xenu story]], as presented in the episode, "utterly ridiculous". He compared Scientology's mythology to Christianity's [[Virgin Birth]] and the [[transubstantiation]], stating, "Let's be honest, these beliefs are just as ridiculous as those of Scientology."<ref name="greto" /><ref name="hanley" /> Hanley went on to delve into a philosophical analysis of the "evidential weight" of popularity and tradition in determining the "robustness" of beliefs.<ref name="greto" />

[[Southwest Minnesota State University]] philosophy professor Robert Arp also analyzed the philosophical and cultural aspects of the episode, in his book: ''[[South Park and Philosophy: You Know, I Learned Something Today]]''.<ref name="arp">{{cite book|last=Arp|first=Robert (Editor)|coauthors=William Irwin (Series Editor)|title=[[South Park and Philosophy: You Know, I Learned Something Today]]|publisher=Blackwell Publishing (The Blackwell Philosophy & Pop Culture Series)|date=[[2006-12-11]]|pages=27, 59, 60, 118, 120, 132, 137, 138, 140, 224|id=ISBN 1405161604 , ISBN 978-1405161602}}</ref>  Arp analyzed [[Comedy Central]]'s reaction to the episode itself, in a section of his book entitled "2005-2006: Comedy Central Caves".<ref name="arp" /> Arp mentions ''South Park's'' usage of the onscreen caption<U+2014>"This is what Scientologists actually believe."<U+2014>in the episode, noting that the same device was used in the episode "[[All About Mormons]]". In referencing this similar use of the onscreen caption device, Arp seemed to point to an inconsistency in the behavior of Comedy Central relative to the episode. He explained, "By a long shot, this show was more kind to Scientology than was "All About the Mormons" to Mormonism."<ref name="arp" /> He noted Comedy Central had suggested it would not rebroadcast the episode for the second time, though it later announced on [[July 12]], [[2006]] that it would.<ref name="arp" />

===Awards===
The organization [[Fight Against Coercive Tactics Network]], founded by [[Lawrence Wollersheim]], named the ''South Park'' staff their "FACTNet Person(s) of the Year for 2005" for this episode.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Staff
  | first =
  | coauthors =
  | title = FACTNet.org Names South Park TV Show Staff FACTNet Person(s) of the Year for 2005 for their Recent Scientology Tom Cruise John Travolta Episode
  | work = Fight Against Coercive Tactics Network
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = F.A.C.T.Net, Inc.
  | date = November 2005 newsletter, November 20, 2005
  | url = http://www.factnet.org/letters/FACTNewsNovember2005SouthPark.html 
  | accessdate =  }}</ref>

Robert Arp cited the series' winning a [[Peabody Award]] due to its willingness to criticize intolerance in April 2006 as a: "special concern for criticizing and countering intolerance," and the notion that: "the Church of Scientology suffers from the widely held perceptions that it seeks to silence former members and others who criticize its beliefs and practices," as the motivation behind the episode.<ref name="arp" />

The episode was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] on [[July 6]], [[2006]] in the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming less than One Hour)]] category,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.org/downloads/images/2006emmys/PrimetimeNoms.php|title=58th Primetime Emmy Awards|publisher=emmys.org|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> the show's sixth nomination (one of which they won, for 2005's "[[Best Friends Forever]].")<ref>{{cite news|url=http://animatedtv.about.com/b/a/201869.htm|title="South Park" Finally Wins Emmy|publisher=animatedtv.about.com|accessdate=2006-11-04}}</ref> ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode "[[The Seemingly Never-Ending Story]]" was the eventual recipient of the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.org/media/releases/2006/crtvarts2006_rel.pdf|title=Create Arts Emmys winners|publisher=emmys.org|format=[[PDF]]|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref>  ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' writer Tom O'Neil theorized that the "Emmy Award Winning Series" plot device used in the October 2007 episode "[[More Crap]]" may have been a reference to the missed Emmy win for "Trapped in the Closet."<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = O'Neil
  | first = Tom
  | coauthors =
  | title = Did 'South Park' dump on the Emmys?
  | work = [[Los Angeles Times]]
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher =
  | date = October 11, 2007
  | url = http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2007/10/did-south-park-.html
  | accessdate = 2007-10-20 }}
</ref>

It was also among [[Comedy Central]]'s list of "10 South Parks That Changed The World,"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newpaltz.edu/oracle/article.cfm?id=2563|title=South Park: Crude and Rude as Ever|publisher=newpaltz.edu|accessdate=2006-11-10}}</ref> which started airing at [[September 24]], [[2006]] in anticipation for the premiere of the second half of South Park's tenth season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.awn.com/index.php?ltype=cat&category1=Television&newsitem_no=17990|title=Comedy Central to Air South Park Episodes That Changed the World|publisher=news.awn.com|date=2006-09-19|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref>

==Appearances in media==
The scene where Cruise enters the closet is referenced in the ''South Park'' segment of the opening of the [[58th Primetime Emmy Awards]] on [[August 27]], [[2006]], in which [[Conan O'Brien]] is trying to get to the show, but suddenly appears in Stan's room in an animated form. Stan begins yelling at him as he runs into the nearby closet. Immediately following the entrance he exits the closet and says, "There's someone else in there," referring to Cruise, and leaves the door open. Cruise then pops out and closes the door.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-conanthedestroyer,0,1530551.story |title=Conan the Destroyer |accessdate=2006-08-28 |publisher=zap2it.com}}</ref>

There is a scene in the film ''[[The Bridge (Scientology film)|The Bridge]]'' by Brett Hanover, where two young women inquiring about Scientology ask a Scientology volunteer if she has seen "Trapped in the Closet," the ''South Park'' episode.  The volunteer answers that she has not heard of ''South Park'', and the two women later leave during the middle of an orientation video.<ref>{{cite video
  | people = Hanover, Brett, Director
  | title = [[The Bridge (Scientology film)|The Bridge]]
  | medium = Released as a free download over the internet on September 10, 2006 by the filmmaker: ''Film Credits: The Bridge' is licensed as royalty-free digital media, and may be distributed online for personal viewing without permission. All offline distribution rights are reserved by Brett Hanover.''
  | publisher =
  | location =
  | date =  }}</ref>

